{"title_page": "Shaquille Quarterman", "text_new": "{{short description|American football linebacker}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Shaquille Quarterman\n|school=Miami Hurricanes\n|currentnumber=55\n|currentposition=[[Linebacker]]\n|class= Senior\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=1\n|weight_lb=241\n|highschool=[[Oakleaf High School]]<br>([[Orange Park, Florida]])\n|pastschools=\n*[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] (2016\u20132019)\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2016 Russell Athletic Bowl]]\n*[[2017 Orange Bowl]]\n*[[2018 Pinstripe Bowl]]\n|highlights=\n*2\u00d7 First Team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] ([[2018 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2018]], [[2019 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2019]])\n*Second Team All-ACC ([[2017 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2017]])\n|espn=4037468\n}}\n\n'''Shaquille Quarterman''' is an [[American football]] [[linebacker]] for the [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami Hurricanes]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nQuarterman grew up in [[Orange Park, Florida]] and attended [[Oakleaf High School]]. He posted 137 tackles, 8 tackles for loss and 3.5 sacks for the Knights in his junior season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://caneswarning.com/2015/01/27/miami-hurricanes-recruiting-shaquille-quarterman-talks-junior-day/}}|title=Miami Hurricanes Recruiting: Shaquille Quarterman Talks Junior Day And More|first=Andrew|last=Ferrelli|website=CanesWarning.com|publisher=[[FanSided]]|date=January 27, 2015|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> He was rated four-stars and as one of the top 10 inside linebacker recruits in the nation by ''[[ESPN]]'', ''[[Scout.com]]'', ''[[Rivals.com]]'' and ''[[247Sports.com|247Sports]]'' and committed to play [[college football]] at the [[Miami Hurricanes football|University of Miami]] during his junior year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caneswatch.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2015/10/05/recruiting-um-commit-shaquille-quarterman-destroyed-a-quarterback/|title=Recruiting: UM commit Shaquille Quarterman destroyed a quarterback|first=Matt|last=Porter|website=Canes Watch|publisher=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|date=October 5, 2015|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> As a senior, Quarterman made 101 tackles and was named the Regional Defensive Player of the Year by ''[[The Florida Times-Union]]'' and played in the [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-America Bowl]] after the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.claytodayonline.com/stories/ums-next-great-linebacker,3097|title=UM\u2019s next great linebacker?|first=Susan|last=Miller Degnan|website=ClayTodayOnline.com|publisher=[[Miami Herald]]|date=July 20, 2016|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> He finished his high school career with 412 tackles (23.5 for loss) and six sacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=ncf&id=17250103|title=Hurricanes have precocious freshman at middle linebacker|website=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=August 8, 2016|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nQuarterman enrolled early at Miami and was named a starter at inside linebacker for the Hurricanes going into his freshman season. He started all 13 Miami's games and finished second on the team with 84 tackles, with 10 going for a loss, and three sacks and was named was named third team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) by the league's coaches and honorable mention by the media. Quarteman was also named a freshman All-American by ESPN and Pro Football Focus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-hurricanes/fl-sp-um-football-acc-20170715-story.html|title=Leaner, stronger Quarterman hungry to lead Hurricanes defense|first=Christy|last=Cabrera Chirinos|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|date=July 15, 2017|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> As a sophomore, Quarterman was named second team All-ACC after again finishing second on the team in tackles with 83 with seven tackles for loss and 2.5 sacks with five passes broken up.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-hurricanes/fl-sp-um-hurricanes-shaquille-quarterman-espn-top-50-story.html|title=UM's Shaq Quarterman named one of ESPN's top 50 college football players|first=Christy|last=Cabrera Chirinos|work=Sun-Sentinel|date=August 8, 2018|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> He was named first team All-ACC in his junior season after recording 82 tackles, 14 tackles for loss, six sacks, one interception, two pass breakups, six quarterback hurries, one forced fumbles and one fumble recovery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sunherald.com/sports/college/article223795995.html|title=Miami Hurricanes star LB Shaq Quarterman to return for senior season and skip NFL Draft|first=Susan|last=Miller Degnan|work=[[Sun Herald]]|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> Following the season Quarterman contemplated forgoing his final season of NCAA eligibility to enter the [[2019 NFL Draft]] but ultimately decided to return to Miami for his senior year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/acc/university-of-miami/article223795995.html|title=Miami Hurricanes star LB Shaq Quarterman to return for senior season and skip NFL Draft|work=Miami Herald|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nQuarterman was named a preseason All-American by the [[Associated Press]] and several other media outlets, as well as to the watchlists for the [[Butkus Award|Butkus]] and [[Chuck Bednarik Award]]s, going into his senior season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jacksonville.com/sports/20190820/shaquille-quarterman-named-preseason-all-american|title=Shaquille Quarterman named preseason All-American|work=[[The Florida Times-Union]]|date=August 20, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stateoftheu.com/2019/7/23/20706457/miami-hurricanes-football-lbs-michael-pinckney-shaquille-quarterman-named-to-butkus-award-watchlist|title=LBs Michael Pinckney, Shaquille Quarterman named to Butkus Award Watchlist|first=Cameron|last=Underwood|website=StateOfTheU.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=July 23, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> Quarterman finished the season with 107 tackles, 15.5 tackles for loss, one sack, and one forced fumble and was again named first team All-ACC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/miami/Article/Miami-Hurricanes-Football-LB-Shaq-Quarterman-shares-thoughts-on-why-UM-struggled-in-2019-142234825/|title=LB Shaq Quarterman shares thoughts on why UM struggled in 2019|first=David|last=Lake|website=247Sports.com|date=January 15, 2020|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://hurricanesports.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=12449 Miami Hurricanes bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quarterman, Shaquille}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Miami Hurricanes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Orange Park, Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jacksonville, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football linebacker}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Shaquille Quarterman\n|school=Miami Hurricanes\n|currentnumber=55\n|currentposition=[[Linebacker]]\n|class= Senior\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=1\n|weight_lb=241\n|highschool=[[Oakleaf High School]]<br>([[Orange Park, Florida]])\n|pastschools=\n*[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] (2016\u20132019)\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2016 Russell Athletic Bowl]]\n*[[2017 Orange Bowl]]\n*[[2018 Pinstripe Bowl]]\n|highlights=\n*2\u00d7 First Team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] ([[2018 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2018]], [[2019 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2019]])\n*Second Team All-ACC ([[2017 Atlantic Coast Conference football season|2017]])\n|espn=4037468\n}}\n\n'''Shaquille Quarterman''' is an [[American football]] [[linebacker]] for the [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami Hurricanes]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nQuarterman grew up in [[Orange Park, Florida]] and attended [[Oakleaf High School]]. He posted 137 tackles, 8 tackles for loss and 3.5 sacks for the Knights in his junior season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://caneswarning.com/2015/01/27/miami-hurricanes-recruiting-shaquille-quarterman-talks-junior-day/}|title=Miami Hurricanes Recruiting: Shaquille Quarterman Talks Junior Day And More|first=Andrew|last=Ferrelli|website=CanesWarning.com|publisher=[[FanSided]]|date=January 27, 2015|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> He was rated four-stars and as one of the top 10 inside linebacker recruits in the nation by ''[[ESPN]]'', ''[[Scout.com]]'', ''[[Rivals.com]]'' and ''[[247Sports.com|247Sports]]'' and committed to play [[college football]] at the [[Miami Hurricanes football|University of Miami]] during his junior year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caneswatch.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2015/10/05/recruiting-um-commit-shaquille-quarterman-destroyed-a-quarterback/|title=Recruiting: UM commit Shaquille Quarterman destroyed a quarterback|first=Matt|last=Porter|website=Canes Watch|publisher=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|date=October 5, 2015|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> As a senior, Quarterman made 101 tackles and was named the Regional Defensive Player of the Year by ''[[The Florida Times-Union]]'' and played in the [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-America Bowl]] after the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.claytodayonline.com/stories/ums-next-great-linebacker,3097|title=UM\u2019s next great linebacker?||first=Susan|last=Miller Degnan|website=ClayTodayOnline.com|publisher=[[Miami Herald]]|date=July 20, 2016|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> He finished his high school career with 412 tackles (23.5 for loss) and six sacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire?section=ncf&id=17250103|title=Hurricanes have precocious freshman at middle linebacker|website=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=August 8, 2016|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nQuarterman enrolled early at Miami and was named a starter at inside linebacker for the Hurricanes going into his freshman season. He started all 13 Miami's games and finished second on the team with 84 tackles, with 10 going for a loss, and three sacks and was named was named third team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) by the league's coaches and honorable mention by the media. Quarteman was also named a freshman All-American by ESPN and Pro Football Focus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-hurricanes/fl-sp-um-football-acc-20170715-story.html|title=Leaner, stronger Quarterman hungry to lead Hurricanes defense|first=Christy|last=Cabrera Chirinos|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|date=July 15, 2017|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> As a sophomore, Quarterman was named second team All-ACC after again finishing second on the team in tackles with 83 with seven tackles for loss and 2.5 sacks with five passes broken up.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-hurricanes/fl-sp-um-hurricanes-shaquille-quarterman-espn-top-50-story.html|title=UM's Shaq Quarterman named one of ESPN's top 50 college football players|first=Christy|last=Cabrera Chirinos|work=Sun-Sentinel|date=August 8, 2018|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> He was named first team All-ACC in his junior season after recording 82 tackles, 14 tackles for loss, six sacks, one interception, two pass breakups, six quarterback hurries, one forced fumbles and one fumble recovery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sunherald.com/sports/college/article223795995.html|title=Miami Hurricanes star LB Shaq Quarterman to return for senior season and skip NFL Draft|first=Susan|last=Miller Degnan|work=[[Sun Herald]]|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> Following the season Quarterman contemplated forgoing his final season of NCAA eligibility to enter the [[2019 NFL Draft]] but ultimately decided to return to Miami for his senior year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/acc/university-of-miami/article223795995.html|title=Miami Hurricanes star LB Shaq Quarterman to return for senior season and skip NFL Draft|work=Miami Herald|date=January 1, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nQuarterman was named a preseason All-American by the [[Associated Press]] and several other media outlets, as well as to the watchlists for the [[Butkus Award|Butkus]] and [[Chuck Bednarik Award]]s, going into his senior season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jacksonville.com/sports/20190820/shaquille-quarterman-named-preseason-all-american|title=Shaquille Quarterman named preseason All-American|work=[[The Florida Times-Union]]|date=August 20, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stateoftheu.com/2019/7/23/20706457/miami-hurricanes-football-lbs-michael-pinckney-shaquille-quarterman-named-to-butkus-award-watchlist|title=LBs Michael Pinckney, Shaquille Quarterman named to Butkus Award Watchlist|first=Cameron|last=Underwood|website=StateOfTheU.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=July 23, 2019|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> Quarterman finished the season with 107 tackles, 15.5 tackles for loss, one sack, and one forced fumble and was again named first team All-ACC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/miami/Article/Miami-Hurricanes-Football-LB-Shaq-Quarterman-shares-thoughts-on-why-UM-struggled-in-2019-142234825/|title=LB Shaq Quarterman shares thoughts on why UM struggled in 2019|first=David|last=Lake|website=247Sports.com|date=January 15, 2020|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://hurricanesports.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=12449 Miami Hurricanes bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quarterman, Shaquille}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Miami Hurricanes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Orange Park, Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jacksonville, Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and high school:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaquille_Quarterman"}
{"title_page": "Paul Fireman", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Fireman\n| image              = \n[[File:Paul Fireman.jpg|thumb|Paul Fireman]]\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = February 14, 1944\n| birth_place        = Cambridge, MA\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| employer           = Fireman Capital Partners\n| occupation         = Businessman and Humanitarian\n| residence          = \n| networth           = {{gain}} US$1.1 [[1,000,000,000|billion]] (August 2018)<ref name=ForbesBillionaires>[https://www.forbes.com/profile/paul-fireman/?list=billionaires The World's Billionaires: \"Paul Fireman\"], Forbes.com; accessed June 11, 2016.</ref>\n| spouse             = Phyllis<ref name=rynecki/>\n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Fireman''' is an [[United States|American]] businessman and humanitarian, who for 26 years led [[Reebok|Reebok International, Ltd]]. as Chairman and CEO to become one of the most popular athletic shoe companies worldwide. Beyond financial success, he is well known as a business visionary and a champion for human rights. Fireman challenged corporate America to become more socially responsible and demonstrated that all corporations could succeed financially, while simultaneously serving the public good. He sold Reebok to Adidas in 2006, but his life and business ventures continue to reflect his philanthropy in serving people and communities throughout the country today. \n\n==Early Life and Education==\nFireman was born February 14, 1944 in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]] to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref name=rynecki>{{cite news|last1=Rynecki|first1=David|title=FIREMAN'S FANTASY|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2005/10/17/8358052/index.htm|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=Fortune|date=17 October 2005}}</ref> and raised in the working-class city of [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], also called 'Shoe City'. Fireman grew up with an insatiable love for golf and as a 10-year-old, caddied at [[Thorny Lea Golf Club]] in his hometown. He viewed golf as \u201ca code of conduct, a way of life, and a tremendous character builder.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He attended high school at [[Tabor Academy (Massachusetts)|Tabor Academy]], a private secondary school in Marion, MA and matriculated to [[Boston University]], but did not graduate.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last1=AP|title=The Man Who Made Reebok Jump High|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/aug/15/business/fi-reebok15|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=LA Times|date=15 August 2005}}</ref> \n\n==Personal Life==\n\nPaul Fireman and his wife Phyllis<ref name=\"lat\" /> (n\u00e9e Brenner) grew up in [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton, MA]] and met at age 12 at a YMHA mixer. Paul states it was love at first sight and said, \u201cI knew the minute I met her it was my destiny\u201d (Interview with Paul Fireman April 2020). They were married in May 1964 and have three grown children and nine grandchildren.\n[[File:Paul and Phyllis Fireman.jpg|thumb|Paul and Phyllis (Brenner) Fireman at a junior high school dance in 1957.|alt=]]\n\nFireman and his wife, Phyllis, are competitive bridge players. In 2014, his team won the Roth Open Swiss Teams at the Summer North American Bridge Championship (NABC) in Las Vegas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/massachusetts/newton/chestnut-hill-native-wins-national-title-north-american-bridge-championship|title=Chestnut Hill native wins national title at North American Bridge Championship|date=2014-08-19|website=Newton, MA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and subsequently captured the bronze medal representing the U.S. in Chennai, India at the World Bridge Championships in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldbridge.org/competitions/wbf-championships/world-bridge-teams-championships/the-bermuda-bowl/|title=The Bermuda Bowl {{!}} World Bridge Federation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\nFireman began his career at age 18 working in the family business, Boston Camping, selling outdoor sporting goods and fishing tackle for 15 years.<ref name=\"lat\" /> After starting in the warehouse, he moved his way up through the business eventually running it with his brother. As the family business declined, Fireman sought new opportunities. \n\nWhile attending a sporting goods show in Chicago in 1979 Fireman met Joe Foster, the owner of a British running shoe company founded in 1895 called Reebok.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/reebok-cofounder-shares-3-rules-for-startup-success-2017-4|title=Reebok co-founder shares 3 rules for startup success|last=Johnson|first=Kieron|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Fireman acquired the North American sales rights to [[Reebok]] in 1979 and eventually bought the British-based parent company outright in 1984.<ref name=\"lat\" /><ref name=\"healy\" /> Reebok capitalized on the increasing popularity of aerobics in California and introduced the world\u2019s first aerobic shoe designed specifically for women in 1982 called Freestyle. Riding the success of the Freestyle shoe as the aerobics craze swept across America, Fireman grew the company and Reebok issued an [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in 1985.<ref name=\"lat\" /> In 1986, Reebok surpassed Nike as the top-selling manufacturer of athletic shoes in the United States, second only in the world to Adidas. Starting in 1986, Reebok acquired several companies to create a multinational corporation, including Avia, a rival athletic shoemaker; John A. Frye, the prestigious and stylish boot maker; Rockport, a company known for its sporting and casual shoes; and [[Ellesse]], an Italian company known for making expensive athletic shoes and clothing. Later acquisitions included [[Boston Whaler]] and The Hockey Company ([[CCM (ice hockey)|CCM]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/reebok-to-buy-ccm-jofa-koho-brands-in-329-million-us-takeover-1.474982|title=Reebok to buy CCM, Jofa, Koho brands in $329 million US takeover|last=|first=|date=April 8, 2004|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Starting in 2000 Reebok signed multiyear, exclusive licensing deals with the [[National Football League|NFL]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/20/sports/pro-football-reebok-strikes-exclusive-deal-with-nfl.html|title=PRO FOOTBALL; Reebok Strikes Exclusive Deal With N.F.L.|date=2000-12-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reporter|first=a Wall Street Journal Staff|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB996707098368148995|title=Reebok Reaches Deal With NBA To Become Its Exclusive Outfitter|date=2001-08-02|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>, and [[National Hockey League|NHL]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/09/15/reebok-nhl-adidas/|title=Reebok passes the NHL puck to Adidas|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. \n\nDuring his tenure at Reebok, Fireman challenged corporate America to become more socially responsible and proved that corporations can financially succeed while serving the public good. He worked diligently to improve human rights worldwide. In 1986, Reebok became one of the first companies to pull out of South Africa because of the country's practice of [[apartheid]] and two years later Reebok sponsored the Amnesty International Human Rights Now tour. Fireman subsequently established the annual Reebok Human Rights Awards in 1988 recognizing activists under the age of 30 who exposed and reduced human rights atrocities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fireman|first=Paul|title=From the Pain Come the Dream: The Recipients of the Reebok Human Rights Award|publisher=Umbrage|year=2003|isbn=1884167357|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>\n\nFireman sold Reebok to [[Adidas]] in 2005.<ref name=\"healy\">{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Beth|title=Paul Fireman takes another shot|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/06/10/reebok_founder_fireman_returns_to_sneaker_business_with_20m_stake_in_colorado_firm/|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=The Boston Globe|date=10 June 2011}}</ref> He is currently the Chairman of Fireman Capital Partners, a Boston-based, consumer-focused private equity firm founded in 2008 with his son Dan, the firm\u2019s Managing Partner.<ref name=\"healy\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firemancapital.com/team/dan-fireman/|title=Dan Fireman {{!}} Fireman Capital Partners {{!}} Boston Massachusetts|website=www.firemancapital.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Golf Course Development==\n\nFireman has been active in golf course development and in 1991 he purchased Willowbend Country Club ([[Mashpee, Massachusetts|Mashpee, MA]]). The development of additional courses followed that included Rio Mar Resort and Country Club ([[Puerto Rico]]), Costa Caribe Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), Coco Beach Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), The Ranch Golf Club ([[Southwick, Massachusetts|Southwick, MA]]), and Starr Pass Club ([[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson, AZ]]).<ref name=\"rynecki\" />\n[[File:Liberty-National-Golf-Course-e1575328328742.jpg|thumb|LIberty National Golf Course with a view of the 18th hole and clubhouse. Lower Manhattan with the Freedom Tower is in the background. ]]\n[[Liberty National Golf Club]] ([[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City, NJ]]) is Fireman\u2019s most impressive foray in to the world of golf. In 1995 Fireman purchased a mile of neglected and decaying New Jersey shoreline along the Hudson River that was an eyesore. The land the Liberty National lies upon has a unique and storied history including an ammunition depot during World War I, and a prisoner of war camp during World War II, and more recently as an oil refinery and warehouse for industrial goods. However, the land when Fireman originally toured the site was \u201ca toxic moonscape of corroded oil tanks, contaminated soil, and rusting warehouses.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/24/golf-barclays-pga-lifestyle-sports-golf-liberty-national.html|title=Inside A $250 Million Golf Course|last=Bertoni|first=Steven|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \u201cI loved the site and the historical value with the Statue of Liberty, and the city, and it was on the water,\u201d Fireman says. \u201cI just plunged into it because I thought it would be a phenomenal golf site and improve the world. And I was just crazy enough to do it.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> At Fireman\u2019s expense, the toxic land was cleaned to remove all residual debris, capped, and covered with 6 million cubic feet of soil that was brought in by truck to create the course<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.golfchannel.com/video/2017-presidents-cup-liberty-national-golf-club-feature|title=2017 Presidents Cup: Liberty National Golf Club feature|website=Golf Channel|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>.\n\nSince its opening in 2006, Liberty National has hosted three [[FedEx Cup]] playoff tournaments ([[The Barclays]] in 2009, 2013 and [[The Northern Trust]] in 2019) and [[Presidents Cup|the Presidents Cup]] in 2017. Liberty National also hosts junior golf tournaments, the First Tee of New Jersey, and local high school golf teams from Jersey City practice and play their home matches at the course.  \n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nThe Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation was created in 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.ppffound.org/about/|title=The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Since its inception, the foundation has distributed over $165 million to charitable organizations with a focus primarily on improving the communities of both Massachusetts and New Jersey.\n\nAddressing homelessness has been a major initiative of the foundation. One Family Inc. was created to preventing family homelessness through advocacy, education, and innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.onefamilyinc.org|title=One Family, Inc.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Using a multi-pronged approach, One Family advocates for public policies that will increase affordable housing and provide services to families experiencing or who are at risk for homelessness with an aim to promote permanent solutions to homelessness. The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Foundation also joined with other donors to create Home Funders, a collaborative fund that finances very affordable rental housing for low-income families in Massachusetts.\n\nFireman is a strong supporter of [[The First Tee]] whose mission is to impact the lives of young people by providing educational programs that build character, instill life-enhancing values and promote healthy habits through the game of golf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/The_First_Tee/Fireman_Donation/prweb12989117.htm|title=Paul and Dan Fireman Show Support For The First Tee Chapters of New Jersey With a Unique Donation|website=PRWeb|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.hunter-pr.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/TFT-NJ-Mentees.pdf|title=Paul Fireman Meets Mentees from New Jersey First Tee Chapters|date=May 12, 2016|work=Hunter Public Relations|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith the COVID-19 pandemic sweeping through the United States, the Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation rapidly acted in March 2020 by making impactful donations to the Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macovid19relieffund.org/|title=Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund|website=www.macovid19relieffund.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Boston Resiliency Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/treasury/boston-resiliency-fund|title=Boston Resiliency Fund|date=2020-03-16|website=Boston.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Jersey City COVID-19 Response Fund, and the New Jersey Pandemic Relief Fund. \n[[File:Paul and Phyllis Fireman after donating Bullard Thermal Imaging Cameras to the Brockton City Firefighters.jpg|thumb|Paul and Phyllis Fireman after donating Bullard Thermal Imaging Cameras to the Brockton City Fire Department in 2000. |alt=]]\n\n==Awards==\n\nThe Academy of Achievement\u2019s Golden Plate Award, 1987\n\nThurgood Marshall Corporate Leadership Award\n\nNortheastern University Commencement Speaker and Honorary Degree, Doctor of Humanities, 1990<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.northeastern.edu/services/archives-special-collections/northeastern-history/commencement-speakers-honorary-degrees|title=Commencement Speakers & Honorary Degrees {{!}} Northeastern University Library|website=library.northeastern.edu|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nBabson College, Honorary Degree, LL.D. Doctor of Laws, 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/academics/centers-and-institutes/the-arthur-m-blank-center-for-entrepreneurship/awards/academy-of-distinguished-entrepreneurs/inductees/fireman-paul/#|title=fireman-paul|last=College|first=Babson|website=www.babson.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nTabor Academy Lifetime Achievement Award, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taboracademy.org/alumni/alumni-recognition|title=Alumni Recognition {{!}} Tabor Academy|website=www.taboracademy.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nSuffolk University Commencement Speaker and Honorary Degree, Doctor of Commerce, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTw0GX4nVXs&feature=emb_logo|title=Paul Fireman Suffolk University Commencement Speech|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMannie Jackson Award, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/news/paul-fireman-bill-self-and-steve-smith-named-winners-2015-mannie-jackson-basketballs-human-spirit-award/|title=The Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame :: Paul Fireman, Bill Self and Steve Smith Named Winners of 2015 Mannie Jackson - Basketball\u2019s Human Spirit Award|website=www.hoophall.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fireman, Paul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Fireman\n| image              = \n[[File:Paul Fireman.jpg|thumb|Paul Fireman]]\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = February 14, 1944\n| birth_place        = Cambridge, MA\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| employer           = Fireman Capital Partners\n| occupation         = Businessman and Humanitarian\n| residence          = \n| networth           = {{gain}} US$1.1 [[1,000,000,000|billion]] (August 2018)<ref name=ForbesBillionaires>[https://www.forbes.com/profile/paul-fireman/?list=billionaires The World's Billionaires: \"Paul Fireman\"], Forbes.com; accessed June 11, 2016.</ref>\n| spouse             = Phyllis<ref name=rynecki/>\n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Fireman''' is an [[United States|American]] businessman and humanitarian, who for 26 years led [[Reebok|Reebok International, Ltd]]. as Chairman and CEO to become one of the most popular athletic shoe companies worldwide. Beyond financial success, he is well known as a business visionary and a champion for human rights. Fireman challenged corporate America to become more socially responsible and demonstrated that all corporations could succeed financially, while simultaneously serving the public good. He sold Reebok to Adidas in 2006, but his life and business ventures continue to reflect his philanthropy in serving people and communities throughout the country today. \n\n==Early Life and Education==\nFireman was born February 14, 1944 in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge, MA]] to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref name=rynecki>{{cite news|last1=Rynecki|first1=David|title=FIREMAN'S FANTASY|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2005/10/17/8358052/index.htm|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=Fortune|date=17 October 2005}}</ref> and raised in the working-class city of [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], also called 'Shoe City'. Fireman grew up with an insatiable love for golf and as a 10-year-old, caddied at [[Thorny Lea Golf Club]] in his hometown. He viewed golf as \u201ca code of conduct, a way of life, and a tremendous character builder.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He attended high school at [[Tabor Academy (Massachusetts)|Tabor Academy]], a private secondary school in Marion, MA and matriculated to [[Boston University]], but did not graduate.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last1=AP|title=The Man Who Made Reebok Jump High|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/aug/15/business/fi-reebok15|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=LA Times|date=15 August 2005}}</ref> \n\n==Personal Life==\n\nPaul Fireman and his wife Phyllis<ref name=\"lat\" /> (n\u00e9e Brenner) grew up in [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton, MA]] and met at age 12 at a YMHA mixer. Paul states it was love at first sight and said, \u201cI knew the minute I met her it was my destiny\u201d (Interview with Paul Fireman April 2020). They were married in May 1964 and have three grown children and nine grandchildren.\n[[File:Paul and Phyllis Fireman.jpg|thumb|Paul and Phyllis (Brenner) Fireman at a junior high school dance in 1957.|alt=]]\n\nFireman and his wife, Phyllis, are competitive bridge players. In 2014, his team won the Roth Open Swiss Teams at the Summer North American Bridge Championship (NABC) in Las Vegas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/massachusetts/newton/chestnut-hill-native-wins-national-title-north-american-bridge-championship|title=Chestnut Hill native wins national title at North American Bridge Championship|date=2014-08-19|website=Newton, MA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and subsequently captured the bronze medal representing the U.S. in Chennai, India at the World Bridge Championships in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldbridge.org/competitions/wbf-championships/world-bridge-teams-championships/the-bermuda-bowl/|title=The Bermuda Bowl {{!}} World Bridge Federation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\nFireman began his career at age 18 working in the family business, Boston Camping, selling outdoor sporting goods and fishing tackle for 15 years.<ref name=\"lat\" /> After starting in the warehouse, he moved his way up through the business eventually running it with his brother. As the family business declined, Fireman sought new opportunities. \n\nWhile attending a sporting goods show in Chicago in 1979 Fireman met Joe Foster, the owner of a British running shoe company founded in 1895 called Reebok.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/reebok-cofounder-shares-3-rules-for-startup-success-2017-4|title=Reebok co-founder shares 3 rules for startup success|last=Johnson|first=Kieron|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Fireman acquired the North American sales rights to [[Reebok]] in 1979 and eventually bought the British-based parent company outright in 1984.<ref name=\"lat\" /><ref name=\"healy\" /> Reebok capitalized on the increasing popularity of aerobics in California and introduced the world\u2019s first aerobic shoe designed specifically for women in 1982 called Freestyle. Riding the success of the Freestyle shoe as the aerobics craze swept across America, Fireman grew the company and Reebok issued an [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in 1985.<ref name=\"lat\" /> In 1986, Reebok surpassed Nike as the top-selling manufacturer of athletic shoes in the United States, second only in the world to Adidas. Starting in 1986, Reebok acquired several companies to create a multinational corporation, including Avia, a rival athletic shoemaker; John A. Frye, the prestigious and stylish boot maker; Rockport, a company known for its sporting and casual shoes; and [[Ellesse]], an Italian company known for making expensive athletic shoes and clothing. Later acquisitions included [[Boston Whaler]] and The Hockey Company ([[CCM (ice hockey)|CCM]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/reebok-to-buy-ccm-jofa-koho-brands-in-329-million-us-takeover-1.474982|title=Reebok to buy CCM, Jofa, Koho brands in $329 million US takeover|last=|first=|date=April 8, 2004|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Starting in 2000 Reebok signed multiyear, exclusive licensing deals with the [[National Football League|NFL]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/20/sports/pro-football-reebok-strikes-exclusive-deal-with-nfl.html|title=PRO FOOTBALL; Reebok Strikes Exclusive Deal With N.F.L.|date=2000-12-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reporter|first=a Wall Street Journal Staff|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB996707098368148995|title=Reebok Reaches Deal With NBA To Become Its Exclusive Outfitter|date=2001-08-02|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>, and [[National Hockey League|NHL]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/09/15/reebok-nhl-adidas/|title=Reebok passes the NHL puck to Adidas|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. \n\nDuring his tenure at Reebok, Fireman challenged corporate America to become more socially responsible and proved that corporations can financially succeed while serving the public good. He worked diligently to improve human rights worldwide. In 1986, Reebok became one of the first companies to pull out of South Africa because of the country's practice of [[apartheid]] and two years later Reebok sponsored the Amnesty International Human Rights Now tour. Fireman subsequently established the annual Reebok Human Rights Awards in 1988 recognizing activists under the age of 30 who exposed and reduced human rights atrocities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fireman|first=Paul|title=From the Pain Come the Dream: The Recipients of the Reebok Human Rights Award|publisher=Umbrage|year=2003|isbn=1884167357|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>\n\nFireman sold Reebok to [[Adidas]] in 2005.<ref name=\"healy\">{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Beth|title=Paul Fireman takes another shot|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/06/10/reebok_founder_fireman_returns_to_sneaker_business_with_20m_stake_in_colorado_firm/|accessdate=18 October 2015|publisher=The Boston Globe|date=10 June 2011}}</ref> He is currently the Chairman of Fireman Capital Partners, a Boston-based, consumer-focused private equity firm founded in 2008 with his son Dan, the firm\u2019s Managing Partner.<ref name=\"healy\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firemancapital.com/team/dan-fireman/|title=Dan Fireman {{!}} Fireman Capital Partners {{!}} Boston Massachusetts|website=www.firemancapital.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Golf Course Development==\n\nFireman has been active in golf course development and in 1991 he purchased Willowbend Country Club ([[Mashpee, Massachusetts|Mashpee, MA]]). The development of additional courses followed that included Rio Mar Resort and Country Club ([[Puerto Rico]]), Costa Caribe Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), Coco Beach Golf and Country Club (Puerto Rico), The Ranch Golf Club ([[Southwick, Massachusetts|Southwick, MA]]), and Starr Pass Club ([[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson, AZ]]).<ref name=\"rynecki\" />\n \n[[Liberty National Golf Club]] ([[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City, NJ]]) is Fireman\u2019s most impressive foray in to the world of golf. In 1995 Fireman purchased a mile of neglected and decaying New Jersey shoreline along the Hudson River that was an eyesore. The land the Liberty National lies upon has a unique and storied history including an ammunition depot during World War I, and a prisoner of war camp during World War II, and more recently as an oil refinery and warehouse for industrial goods. However, the land when Fireman originally toured the site was \u201ca toxic moonscape of corroded oil tanks, contaminated soil, and rusting warehouses.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/24/golf-barclays-pga-lifestyle-sports-golf-liberty-national.html|title=Inside A $250 Million Golf Course|last=Bertoni|first=Steven|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \u201cI loved the site and the historical value with the Statue of Liberty, and the city, and it was on the water,\u201d Fireman says. \u201cI just plunged into it because I thought it would be a phenomenal golf site and improve the world. And I was just crazy enough to do it.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libertynationalgc.com/club/scripts/library/view_document.asp?NS=PUBLIC&DN=HISTORY|title=Liberty National\u00a0Club History|website=www.libertynationalgc.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> At Fireman\u2019s expense, the toxic land was cleaned to remove all residual debris, capped, and covered with 6 million cubic feet of soil that was brought in by truck to create the course<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.golfchannel.com/video/2017-presidents-cup-liberty-national-golf-club-feature|title=2017 Presidents Cup: Liberty National Golf Club feature|website=Golf Channel|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>.\n\nSince its opening in 2006, Liberty National has hosted three [[FedEx Cup]] playoff tournaments ([[The Barclays]] in 2009, 2013 and [[The Northern Trust]] in 2019) and [[Presidents Cup|the Presidents Cup]] in 2017. Liberty National also hosts junior golf tournaments, the First Tee of New Jersey, and local high school golf teams from Jersey City practice and play their home matches at the course.  \n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nThe Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation was created in 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.ppffound.org/about/|title=The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Since its inception, the foundation has distributed over $165 million to charitable organizations with a focus primarily on improving the communities of both Massachusetts and New Jersey.\n\nAddressing homelessness has been a major initiative of the foundation. One Family Inc. was created to preventing family homelessness through advocacy, education, and innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=www.onefamilyinc.org|title=One Family, Inc.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Using a multi-pronged approach, One Family advocates for public policies that will increase affordable housing and provide services to families experiencing or who are at risk for homelessness with an aim to promote permanent solutions to homelessness. The Paul and Phyllis Fireman Foundation also joined with other donors to create Home Funders, a collaborative fund that finances very affordable rental housing for low-income families in Massachusetts.\n\nFireman is a strong supporter of [[The First Tee]] whose mission is to impact the lives of young people by providing educational programs that build character, instill life-enhancing values and promote healthy habits through the game of golf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/The_First_Tee/Fireman_Donation/prweb12989117.htm|title=Paul and Dan Fireman Show Support For The First Tee Chapters of New Jersey With a Unique Donation|website=PRWeb|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.hunter-pr.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/TFT-NJ-Mentees.pdf|title=Paul Fireman Meets Mentees from New Jersey First Tee Chapters|date=May 12, 2016|work=Hunter Public Relations|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith the COVID-19 pandemic sweeping through the United States, the Paul and Phyllis Fireman Charitable Foundation rapidly acted in March 2020 by making impactful donations to the Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macovid19relieffund.org/|title=Massachusetts COVID-19 Relief Fund|website=www.macovid19relieffund.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Boston Resiliency Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/treasury/boston-resiliency-fund|title=Boston Resiliency Fund|date=2020-03-16|website=Boston.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>, the Jersey City COVID-19 Response Fund, and the New Jersey Pandemic Relief Fund. \n[[File:Paul and Phyllis Fireman after donating Bullard Thermal Imaging Cameras to the Brockton City Firefighters.jpg|thumb|Paul and Phyllis Fireman after donating Bullard Thermal Imaging Cameras to the Brockton City Fire Department in 2000. |alt=]]\n\n==Awards==\n\nThe Academy of Achievement\u2019s Golden Plate Award, 1987\n\nThurgood Marshall Corporate Leadership Award\n\nNortheastern University Commencement Speaker and Honorary Degree, Doctor of Humanities, 1990<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.northeastern.edu/services/archives-special-collections/northeastern-history/commencement-speakers-honorary-degrees|title=Commencement Speakers & Honorary Degrees {{!}} Northeastern University Library|website=library.northeastern.edu|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nBabson College, Honorary Degree, LL.D. Doctor of Laws, 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/academics/centers-and-institutes/the-arthur-m-blank-center-for-entrepreneurship/awards/academy-of-distinguished-entrepreneurs/inductees/fireman-paul/#|title=fireman-paul|last=College|first=Babson|website=www.babson.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nTabor Academy Lifetime Achievement Award, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taboracademy.org/alumni/alumni-recognition|title=Alumni Recognition {{!}} Tabor Academy|website=www.taboracademy.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nSuffolk University Commencement Speaker and Honorary Degree, Doctor of Commerce, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTw0GX4nVXs&feature=emb_logo|title=Paul Fireman Suffolk University Commencement Speech|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMannie Jackson Award, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/news/paul-fireman-bill-self-and-steve-smith-named-winners-2015-mannie-jackson-basketballs-human-spirit-award/|title=The Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame :: Paul Fireman, Bill Self and Steve Smith Named Winners of 2015 Mannie Jackson - Basketball\u2019s Human Spirit Award|website=www.hoophall.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fireman, Paul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "A111861538968R", "label": "safe", "comment": "\