rds|2019]]\n| Best in Entertainment Sites & Apps \n| ''The Masked Singer'' Social Hub\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=Best in Entertainment Sites & Apps|url=https://shortyawards.com/category/11th/entertainment-apps|website=[[Shorty Awards]]|date=January 28, 2019|archive-url=http://archive.today/poEjN|archive-date=April 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| [[2019 Teen Choice Awards|2019]]\n| Choice Reality TV Show\n| ''The Masked Singer''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=Here Are All the Winners From the 2019 Teen Choice Awards|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8527134/teen-choice-awards-2019-winners-list|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215073036/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8527134/teen-choice-awards-2019-winners-list|archive-date=February 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Spin-offs==\n===''The Masked Singer: After the Mask''===\n[[File:Masked-singer-after-the-mask.png|upright=1|thumb|Logo for the aftershow.|alt=refer to caption]]\nOn April 8, 2020, Fox announced that Cannon will host an [[aftershow]] of the series titled ''The Masked Singer: After the Mask'' on Wednesdays at 9:00 p.m. for four weeks starting on April 22. He will host the show from his house and discuss the outcome of the preceding episode with celebrity guests appearing remotely.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=''The Masked Singer'' After-Show, Hosted by Nick Cannon, to Launch on Fox|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/the-masked-singer-after-the-mask-nick-cannon-fox-1234574761/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Roots|first=Kimberly|title=''The Masked Singer'' to Get Aftershow|url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/08/the-masked-singer-aftershow-nick-cannon-season-3-fox/|website=[[TVLine]]|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In the first episode, [[Kelly Osbourne]], [[JoJo Siwa]], Jeong, and McHale are all set to appear as guests, along with the eliminated celebrity with a performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/masked-singer-aftershow-after-the-mask-jojo-siwa-kelly-osbourne/|title=''Masked Singer'' Sets Alums Kelly Osbourne, JoJo Siwa as Guests for First-Ever Aftershow (Exclusive)|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[TheWrap]]|url-access=registration}}</ref> In the second episode, Ramsay is set to appear as a guest.<ref name=\"VAR Mar 26\"/>\n<!--\n{{Television episode ratings |width=85\n| show_timeslot = y\n\n| refs_col = y\n\n| title1     = After the Mask: The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2\n| date1      = April 22, 2020\n| timeslot1  = Wednesday 9:00 p.m.\n| timeslot_length1 = 4\n| rs1        = \n| viewers1   = \n| dvr1       = \n| dvrv1      = \n| total1     = \n| totalv1    = \n| ref1       = \n\n| title2     = After the Mask: The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6\n| date2      = April 29, 2020\n| rs2        = \n| viewers2   = \n| dvr2       = \n| dvrv2      = \n| total2     = \n| totalv2    = \n| ref2       = \n\n| title3     = After the Mask: A Quarter Mask Crisis: The Quarter Finals\n| date3      = May 6, 2020\n| rs3        = \n| viewers3   = \n| dvr3       = \n| dvrv3      = \n| total3     = \n| totalv3    = \n| ref3       = \n\n| title4     = \n| date4      = May 13, 2020\n| rs4        = \n| viewers4   = \n| dvr4       = \n| dvrv4      = \n| total4     = \n| totalv4    = \n| ref4       = \n}} -->\n\n===''The Masked Dancer''===\nOn January 7, 2020, at the winter [[Television Critics Association]] press tour, Fox Alternative Entertainment and [[Warner Bros. Television]] announced that they had ordered a spin-off series, ''The Masked Dancer'', with [[Ellen DeGeneres]] as executive producer. DeGeneres had previously conducted ''The Masked Dancer'' as a recurring segment on her syndicated [[talk show]] ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' as a self-admitted parody of ''The Masked Singer''. She stated that the show was \"gonna be just as fun and suspenseful, but with a lot more [[krumping]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/the-masked-dancer-fox-partners-with-ellen-degeneres-on-the-masked-singer-spin-off-1202823169/|title=''The Masked Dancer'': Fox Partners With Ellen DeGeneres On ''The Masked Singer'' Spinoff \u2013 TCA|last=White|first=Peter|date=January 7, 2020|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/pug-almost-passes-out-playing-ellen-degeneres-latest-masked-singer-ripoff-video/|title=A Pug Almost Passes Out Playing Ellen DeGeneres' Latest ''Masked Dancer''|date=February 18, 2019|website=[[TheWrap]]|url-access=registration}}</ref> The series was expected to debut in summer 2020, however, due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], production has not yet begun.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/a-puzzle-all-pieces-broadcast-networks-scramble-program-an-uncertain-future-1288828|title=A Puzzle Without All the Pieces: Broadcast Networks Scramble to Program an Uncertain Future|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=April 7, 2020|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\nOn February 12, 2020, it was announced that the show would be getting a live national tour with shows in over forty-five cities. Beginning at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]] on May 28, 2020, the tour will feature two celebrity hosts as well as a local mystery celebrity who is unmasked at the end of each show.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20200212005953/en/MASKED-SINGER-Unveils-45-City-U.S.-National|title=''The Masked Singer'' Unveils 45+ City U.S. National Tour|via=[[Business Wire]]|date=February 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=''The Masked Singer'' Announces Nationwide Concert Tour This Summer|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-concert-tour-summer-1203502739/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> The series has an online store where hoodies, coffee mugs, and phone cases, among others using the show's branding, are available for purchase.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://maskedsingershop.com/|website=The Masked Singer Shop|title=The Masked Singer Merchandise|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On February 24, 2020, toy manufacturer Jazwares announced they had partnered with Fox to release a ''Masked Singer''-inspired karaoke microphone under their \"First Act\" brand. The microphone will include a voice-changing feature and be sold at retail later in the year.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/jazwares-announces-new-first-act-karaoke-microphone-inspired-by-foxs-mega-hit-singing-competition-series-the-masked-singer-301009810.html|title=Jazwares Announces New First Act\u2122 Karaoke Microphone Inspired By Fox's Mega-Hit Singing Competition Series, ''The Masked Singer'' |date=February 24, 2020|publisher=Jazwares|via=[[PR Newswire]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225165959/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/jazwares-announces-new-first-act-karaoke-microphone-inspired-by-foxs-mega-hit-singing-competition-series-the-masked-singer-301009810.html|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.licenseglobal.com/toys-games/ny-toy-fair-jazwares-unveils-ufc-masked-singer-fortnite-and-all-elite-wrestling-toys|title=NY Toy Fair: Jazwares Unveils UFC, ''The Masked Singer'', ''Fortnite'' and All Elite Wrestling Toys|date=February 24, 2020|website=License Global|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410063545/https://www.licenseglobal.com/toys-games/ny-toy-fair-jazwares-unveils-ufc-masked-singer-fortnite-and-all-elite-wrestling-toys|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{sequence\n|prev=''[[The World's Best ]]''<br />[[Super Bowl LIII|2019]]\n|list=[[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|Super Bowl lead-out program]]<br />''The Masked Singer''<br />[[Super Bowl LIV|2020]]\n|next=TBA\n}}\n\n{{The Masked Singer (American TV series)}}\n{{Masked Singer series}}\n{{FOXNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masked Singer, The}}\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Fox Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2010s American music television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American music television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American game shows]]\n[[Category:American television series based on South Korean television series]]\n[[Category:Music competitions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl lead-out programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fox Entertainment]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the current season|The Masked Singer (American season 3)}}\n{{short description|American reality singing competition television show}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name         = The Masked Singer\n| image             = Masked Singer USA Logo.png\n| image_alt         = Title card of ''The Masked Singer''\n| caption           = \n| genre             = [[Reality competition]]<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=Piester|first=Lauren|title=The Secrets of ''The Masked Singer'': Everything We've Learned About TV's Most Mysterious Show|url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|date=February 27, 2019|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703044452/https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|archive-date=July 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| creator            = \n| based_on           = {{based_on|''[[King of Mask Singer]]''|[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]]}}\n| developer          = [[Craig Plestis]]\n| director           = {{unbulleted list|Alex Rudzinski|Brad Duns}}\n| presenter          = [[Nick Cannon]]\n| starring           = {{unbulleted list|[[Ken Jeong]]|[[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]|[[Nicole Scherzinger]]|[[Robin Thicke]]}}\n| narrated           = \n| composer           = \n| executive_producer = {{unbulleted list|Craig Plestis ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Izzie Pick Ibarra ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Rosie Seitchik ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)|Nick Cannon ({{abbr|s.|season}} 3\u2013)}}\n| producer           = \n| company            = {{unbulleted list|[[Endemol Shine North America]] ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1)|Fox Alternative Entertainment ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)}}\n| distributor        = {{unbulleted list|[[Fox Corporation]]|Propagate Content}}\n| location           = \n| camera             = \n| runtime            = 42\u201385 minutes\n| opentheme          = {{theme_song|\"[[Who Are You (The Who song)|Who Are You]]\"|[[The Who]]}}\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| network            = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| channel            = \n| picture_format     = \n| audio_format       = \n| first_run          = \n| released           = \n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| num_seasons        = 3\n| num_episodes       = 36<!-- as of April 15, 2020 -->\n| list_episodes      = List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes\n| preceded_by        = \n| related            = {{unbulletedlist|''The Masked Singer: After the Mask''|''The Masked Dancer''}}\n| website            = https://www.fox.com/the-masked-singer/\n| production_website = https://www.smartdogmedia.com/the-masked-singer\n}}\n\n'''''The Masked Singer''''' is an American [[Reality competition|reality singing competition]] television series featuring celebrities in head-to-toe costumes and face masks that conceal their identities from other contestants, panelists, and an audience. After they perform a cover of a famous song, the panelists and audience vote for their favorite performance and the celebrity with the fewest votes is eliminated from the competition, taking off their mask and revealing their identity. The [[Nick Cannon]]-hosted show was the first in the ''[[Masked Singer]]'' franchise to air outside of Asia, premiering on January 2, 2019, on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]. \n\nThe show employs four permanent panelists\u2014[[Ken Jeong]], [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and [[Robin Thicke]]\u2014to make guesses as to who the celebrities could be after each performance, with a guest panelist often appearing alongside them. While they have received generally unfavorable reviews from critics, the show's costumes have attracted praise. They are designed by Marina Toybina and built by a team who incorporate both [[Haute couture|traditional fashion]] elements and innovative solutions that help the performer sing clearly and move freely on stage. In recognition of the show's costume design, it has won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] and received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination.\n\nThe winners of the first and second seasons were [[T-Pain]] and [[Wayne Brady]], respectively. Extensive measures are taken by the show's production crew to prevent the identities of the contestants from leaking before an episode airs. The episodes themselves have received high television ratings; during the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]], the show was the highest rated new series among adults 18\u201349, leading some commentators to consider the show at the forefront of a new reality television era in the United States. It has spawned numerous spin-offs, including an upcoming dance version and a national tour. Subsequent adaptations of the ''Masked Singer'' franchise worldwide have been credited to the show's success, as has an interest in developing other television series centered on costumes. \n\nThe show is currently in its [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third season]] which premiered as the [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|lead-out program]] on February 2, 2020. During an interview prior to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Rob Wade, President of Alternative Entertainment and Specials at Fox, confirmed that future seasons are planned.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\">{{cite web|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Fox Entertainment's Rob Wade|url=https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|website=TV Formats|date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416012653/https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|archive-date=April 15, 2020|url-status=live|quote=And then ''The Masked Dancer'' is coming up soon. And future cycles of ''The Masked Singer.''}}</ref>\n\n==Panelists and host==\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 450\n| total_height\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1   = Ken Jeong March 2015.jpg\n| alt1     = Ken Jeong\n| caption1 = [[Ken Jeong]]\n| image2   = Jenny McCarthy at E3 2006.jpg\n| alt2     = Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg\n| caption2 = [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| image3   = Nicole Scherzinger 2012.jpg\n| alt3     = Nicole Scherzinger\n| caption3 = [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| image4   = Robin Thicke 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt4     = Robin Thicke\n| caption4 = [[Robin Thicke]]\n| image5   = Nick Cannon by David Shankbone.jpg\n| alt5     = Nick Cannon\n| caption5 = [[Nick Cannon]] \n}}\n\nSince the first season, the permanent panel has consisted of actor and comedian [[Ken Jeong]], television personality [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], recording artist [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and singer-songwriter [[Robin Thicke]], with [[Nick Cannon]] hosting the show.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\">{{cite web|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|title=Fox Orders ''Masked Singer'' Reality Series; Nick Cannon to Host|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102132907/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|archive-date=November 2, 2019|date=August 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThere are often guest panelists that appear as the fifth panelist on the series\u2014occasionally for multiple episodes. In the first season, they were [[Joel McHale]] (episodes 3\u20134), [[J. B. Smoove]] (episode 7), and [[Kenan Thompson]] (episodes 8 and 10). In the second season, they were [[Anthony Anderson]] (episode 6), [[Triumph the Insult Comic Dog]] ([[Robert Smigel]]; episode 7), McHale (episodes 8\u20139), and [[T-Pain]] (episode 10). In the third season, the guest panelists included [[Jamie Foxx]] (episode 1), [[Jason Biggs]] (episode 2), [[Leah Remini]] (episode 3), [[Gabriel Iglesias]] (episode 5), T-Pain (episode 6), McHale (episode 8), [[Will Arnett]] (episode 9), and [[Yvette Nicole Brown]] (episode 11), with [[Sharon Osbourne]] set to appear in the twelfth episode,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-313/313A) \"The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2 / After the Mask: The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref> [[Gordon Ramsay]] in the thirteenth,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-314/314A) \"The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6 / After the Mask: The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox02/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref> and [[Jeff Dye]] in the fourteenth.<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-315/315A) \"A Quarter Mask Crisis: The Quarter Finals / After the Mask: A Quarter Mask Crisis: The Quarter Finals\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox06/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref>\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size:90%; width:30%;\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\"| Panelist timeline\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Panelists\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Seasons\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|2]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n|-\n| [[Ken Jeong]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Robin Thicke]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Joel McHale]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[J.B. Smoove]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Kenan Thompson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Anthony Anderson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Triumph the Comic Insult Dog]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[T-Pain]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jamie Foxx]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jason Biggs]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Leah Remini]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gabriel Iglesias]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Will Arnett]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Yvette Nicole Brown]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Sharon Osbourne]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gordon Ramsay]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jeff Dye]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\n===Conception and development===\n{{quote box|quote=So we're at a restaurant and my back is to the TV. My daughter said Dad, look at this, there's this crazy thing on. I turned around and all the diners were watching the TV screen. I saw a kangaroo in black pleather singing a pop song. At that moment I said, oh my gosh, I love this! It was bizarre. It was flypaper. It was in a foreign language and you didn't know what was going on, and it was still working. I found out that it was a hit format in Korea, it was a hit show in Thailand. And no one had the [U.S.] rights.|source=\u2014Plestis on the creation of ''The Masked Singer''<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\">{{cite magazine|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Craig Plestis|url=https://issuu.com/worldscreen/docs/tv_formats_miptv_2019|page=38|magazine=TV Formats|date=April 2019|via=[[Issuu]]}}</ref>|align=left|width=35%}}\n\n''The Masked Singer'' is based on the popular<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|title=''The Masked Singer'' Boss on Importance of Contestant Secrecy|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706101843/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|archive-date=July 6, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> South Korean series ''[[King of Mask Singer]]''. Television producer [[Craig Plestis]] explained that he first discovered the format during a visit to a small [[Studio City, Los Angeles]], Thai restaurant in October 2017.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Manori|title=How ''Masked Singer'' is reviving costume-led formats|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|website=Television Business International|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407120916/https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|archive-date=April 7, 2019|date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While waiting for dinner, he observed the other patrons staring at a television while an episode of the [[The Mask Singer (season 3)|third season]] of the [[The Mask Singer (Thai TV series)|Thai version]] of the show was playing. Intrigued, Plestis began to research the series and secured the rights to produce an American adaptation within one week in a deal brokered by his agent, Steve Wohl of [[Paradigm Talent Agency]]. He then called Fox executive Rob Wade on a Friday night to schedule a meeting with him the following Monday and worked to create a showcase during the weekend.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/> According to Plestis, Wade was \"scared\" by the show but envisioned its potential. After successfully pitching the show under the condition that he \"could cast enough [[A-list]] celebrities\",<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Bentley|first=Jean|title=''The Masked Singer'': How the Fox Reality Show Scored Top Talent (and Kept It Secret)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713155810/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Plestis began developing the series in November.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Peter|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|title=Fox Developing Remake of Asian Talent Competition ''The Masked Singer''|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521062138/https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|archive-date=May 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2018, executive producer Izzie Pick Ibarra became involved with the show to aid in the casting process and \"[[Americanization|Americanize]]\" the format. Rather than follow the South Korean version in which two singers perform in three rounds, with the winner of the final round facing the winner of the previous episode in an attempt to become the new \"Mask King\", Ibarra opted to air one elimination per night, emphasize the clue packages and guessing component, and have the celebrities wear more extravagant costumes.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> Plestis agreed, wanting to create a [[story arc]] throughout the episodes and\u2014unlike the South Korean series\u2014be able to reuse the costumes.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/> The series was officially ordered by Fox in August 2018.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\"/>\n\n[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]], the rightsholder of the ''Masked Singer'' format, lacked the ability to produce the show. As a result, the [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|first season]]  was produced by [[Endemol Shine North America]] due to Plestis' relationship with the studio. For the [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|second season]], production transitioned to a new in-house studio, Fox Alternative Entertainment, and the show's budget was lowered as a result.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haynes|first=Dade|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed For Third Season, Gets Post-Super Bowl Slot On|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830010304/https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|archive-date=August 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|title=Fox Launching Unscripted Studio With ''The Masked Singer'' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817034711/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|archive-date=August 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Wade said this gave the network further creative control over the series and allowed it to sell merchandise, launch a national tour, and create spin-off show ''The Masked Dancer''.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\"/> Since the second and [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third seasons]], respectively, Rosie Seitchik and Cannon have also served as executive producers.<ref>{{cite press release|title=All-New Special \"The Masked Singer: Super Sneak Peek\" to Air Sunday, September 15, on Fox|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/08/28/all-new-special-the-masked-singer-super-sneak-peek-to-air-sunday-september-15-on-fox-94001/20190828fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|date=August 28, 2019|archive-url=http://archive.today/XApNp|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=''Beat Shazam'' Host Jamie Foxx Touches Down as a Guest Panelist in The Season Three Premiere of ''The Masked Singer'', Following Super Bowl LIV, Sunday, February 2, on Fox|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2020/01/07/beat-shazam-host-jamie-foxx-touches-down-as-a-guest-panelist-in-the-season-three-premiere-of-the-masked-singer-following-super-bowl-liv-sunday-february-2-on-fox-703210/20200107fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]||publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|date=January 7, 2020|archive-url=http://archive.today/XApNp|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Format===\n{{Listen|pos=right|filename=Masked Singer US Monster Voiceover.ogg|title=Monster voiceover|description=A sample of a typical voiceover in a clue package showing how modulation is used to disguise the actual identity of the performers on the show while they give hints about their backgrounds.|format=[[Ogg]]}}\nA group of [[Celebrity|celebrities]] compete on the show anonymously in costumes over a series of episodes. The specific format of the competition varies by season and episode, but generally, most episodes feature four to six celebrities performing a cover of a famous song, and the audience and panelists then vote for their favorite. The celebrity with the fewest votes in an episode is eliminated from the competition and must take off their mask to reveal their identity. This process of elimination continues for a set number of episodes until three contestants remain, and one is declared the winner after they perform again. There is no cash prize for winning, rather, the celebrity wins the \"golden mask trophy\".<ref name=\"PeopleS3\">{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Natalie|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed for Season 3, to Premiere After 2020 Super Bowl|url=https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220055111/https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|archive-date=February 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=From the Banana to the Taco, ''The Masked Singer'' Season 3 Costumes Have Been Revealed|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-season-3-costumes-first-look-photos-1203485426/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231616/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-season-3-costumes-first-look-photos-1203485426/|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Since the second season, the series has also featured a \"smackdown\" round in some episodes in which the two competitors with the fewest votes from their first performances sing again with a second vote occurring, and the performer with the fewest votes is then eliminated.<ref name=\"USA Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Keveney|first=Bill|title=''The Masked Singer'': Producers promise trickier clues, bigger names and crazier costumes|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/09/24/masked-singer-tweaks-rules-for-16-contestant-season-2/2424261001/|website=[[USA Today]]|date=September 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310055251/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/09/24/masked-singer-tweaks-rules-for-16-contestant-season-2/2424261001/|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the third season, the contestants were divided into three subgroups who each performed on three consecutive episodes before returning to the unified performance format afterwards.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\">{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|title=''Masked Singer'' Showrunner Promises Big Changes for Season 3, Says Cast is \"Unbelievably Interesting\"|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207084115/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the singing competition, hints to each masked singer's identity are offered during the show and are referred to as a \"clue package\" by the panelists. Such clues may feature cryptic allusions to what the celebrity is known for or may be more direct references. Pre-taped interviews are also given as hints and feature the celebrities' electronically masked voices. The panelists are given time to speculate the identity of the singer after their performance and are allowed to ask questions or request that the host offer additional clues.<ref name=\"PeopleS3\"/> Banter between the panelists and behind the scenes footage is also incorporated in a typical episode.<ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\">{{cite web|title=''The Masked Singer'': Burning Questions Answered!|url=https://tvline.com/gallery/the-masked-singer-burning-questions-answered/masked-singer-secrets-season-1/|website=[[TVLine]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421165526/http://tvline.com/gallery/the-masked-singer-burning-questions-answered/masked-singer-secrets-season-1/ |archivedate=April 21, 2020|date=February 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIbarra was ecstatic when Cannon agreed to host the show, citing him as her number-one choice for the role because of his personality and experience. Regarding the panelists, she said the production team was less concerned with selecting those with an ability to critique participants' singing abilities than being able to create a comedic tone for the show as one of their goals was to reassure celebrities they would not be ridiculed for choosing to appear. Jeong was the first panelist to be signed on to the series due to his humour and pre-existing knowledge of the South Korean version, followed by McCarthy Wahlberg and Thicke, respectively, due to their enthusiasm regarding the concept, and Scherzinger for her positivity and experience as a singer.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/> Scherzinger said the producers did not test her [[popular culture|pop culture]] knowledge before being selected as a panelist.<ref name=\"PAR Oct 9\">{{cite web|last=Cohn|first=Paulette|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Nicole Scherzinger on Guessing Who's Behind the Mask and a Possible Pussycat Dolls Reunion|url=https://parade.com/934239/paulettecohn/the-masked-singers-nicole-scherzinger-on-guessing-whos-behind-the-mask-and-a-possible-pussycat-dolls-reunion/|website=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|date=October 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216153630/https://parade.com/934239/paulettecohn/the-masked-singers-nicole-scherzinger-on-guessing-whos-behind-the-mask-and-a-possible-pussycat-dolls-reunion/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 28, 2019, Osbourne revealed on ''[[The Talk (talk show)|The Talk]]'' she was originally supposed to be signed on as a panelist for the series; those plans fell through after being contractually obligated to appear on ''[[The X Factor (British TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Furdyk|first=Brent|url=https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|title=Sharon Osbourne Shreds Simon Cowell For Firing Her From ''The X Factor'' Because He \"Thought I Was Too Old\"|website=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada|ET Canada]]|date=March 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330152540/https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThrough agents, the show's producers reach out to celebrities, or vice versa.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=''The Masked Singer'': How the Eagle fooled his old colleague Jenny McCarthy ago|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/10/the-masked-singer-the-eagle-interview/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=October 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230114730/https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/10/the-masked-singer-the-eagle-interview/|archive-date=December 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ibarra described casting for the series' first season as less difficult than she predicted due to her strategy of sending the possible participants sketches of costumes that might be featured on the series. She said many of the celebrities had emotional reactions when presented with the proposed costumes and that they were excited to use the show to reinvent their [[reputation|public image]]. T-Pain, the winner of the first season, said he was skeptical about the series until he saw the costume choices, citing the opportunity to wear the Monster outfit as his motivation for participating in the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jensen|first=Erin|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|title=''Masked Singer'' winner T-Pain first deemed show \"probably the stupidest thing\" he'd heard|website=[[USA Today]]|date=March 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111040704/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Conversely, [[Wayne Brady]], the winner of the second season, was approached by producers to appear in the first season but turned them down after being confused about the show's concept.<ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\">{{cite web|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|title=''The Masked Singer'' Winner Interview: \"It's the First Time in My Life I Kept a Secret Months on End\"|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110134353/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|archive-date=January 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the success of the first season, Brady was among an increased number of celebrities interested in participating in the second.<ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/> Those who are not professional singers send the producers clips of them singing as a quasi-audition before participating in the series.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/>\n\n===Security===\n[[File:Masked Singer Dont Talk to Me.png|thumb|left|upright=1.1|alt=refer to caption|While on set, the participants wear an oversized sweatshirt with the words \"don't talk to me!\" on the front to keep their identities a secret.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/>]]\nBefore each of the competitors is unmasked, the show's staff undertakes significant security measures to prevent the participants' identities from leaking, many of which, according to Plestis, originate from his visits to the sets of the South Korean and Thai versions of the show.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As a result, he says the series has two [[bible (screenwriting)|bibles]]: one related to the format and a second, larger one for security measures.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Everyone involved in the series signs a [[non-disclosure agreement]] which prevents them from discussing any revealing information about the outcome of an episode with anyone until it airs on television. After the celebrities have been confirmed to appear on the show, they are allowed to inform a few others who also sign one.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\"/> Only about twenty-five people know the contestants' real names during a season, though they never refer to them as such on set, in emails, or during phone calls regarding the show. To prevent their identities from being revealed in the event of a leak or hack, all documents (except the contract) only list the celebrities' code or costume name. Their contract with the show does give their real name, however, the series' name\u2014''The Masked Singer''\u2014is not listed anywhere on it.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"EW Sep 26\">{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=The Ice Cream speaks! Here's how ''The Masked Singer'' recruited the mysterious celebrity|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/26/the-masked-singer-ice-cream-tyler-ninja-blevins/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211102409/https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/26/the-masked-singer-ice-cream-tyler-ninja-blevins/|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VAR Dec 11\">{{cite web|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|title=Seal's Kids Had No Idea He Was Competing on ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/the-masked-singer-seal-the-leopard-children-secret-1203432422/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408060210/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/the-masked-singer-seal-the-leopard-children-secret-1203432422/|archive-date=April 8, 2020|date=December 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBefore arriving on the show's set, the participants and their family, friends, and agents are disguised and driven from a neutral location.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> The manager of [[Joey Fatone]], the Rabbit in the first season, said he was picked up at a [[7-Eleven]] near [[Television City]], given a disguise, and then driven inside the gate.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> Likewise, [[Adrienne Bailon]], the Flamingo in the second season, said she was taken to the set inside of an unmarked black car and only discussed her involvement on the show with producers in a \"secret warehouse\".<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> The set has different access levels<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> and each participant is escorted to and from their trailers located outside of it by security guards while disguised with a mask, visor, gloves, oversized sweatshirt, and pants to prevent their skin from showing.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=''The Masked Singer'' Skeleton admits he got a call from David Letterman weeks ago|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/16/the-masked-singer-skeleton-paul-shaffer-interview/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=October 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218174340/https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/16/the-masked-singer-skeleton-paul-shaffer-interview/|archive-date=December 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Scherzinger, the panelists have personal parking spaces next to the studio's doors and are escorted by security directly to their dressing rooms after arriving.<ref name=\"PAR Oct 9\"/> While inside, Jeong stated that he avoids walking through the same hall as a disguised celebrity so his guesses are as genuine as possible.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hearon|first=Sarah|title=Ken Jeong Reveals How ''Masked Singer'' Judges Avoid Running Into Contestants on Set|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/ken-jeong-on-how-masked-singer-judges-avoid-contestants-on-set/|website=[[Us Weekly]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026125601/https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/ken-jeong-on-how-masked-singer-judges-avoid-contestants-on-set/|archive-date=October 26, 2019|date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe series' security team is almost as large as the production crew and all are tasked with keeping the contestants as isolated from each other as possible.<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> [[Margaret Cho]], the Poodle in the first season, stated she never saw another masked participant due to the performers' rehearsals occurring at varying times and locations.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> Only \"towards the middle of the competition, once [he] was blended into a group\", Brady said he was able to hear other performers singing and recognize their voices while passing the sound stage during rehearsals.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=Fox says he came to The Masked Singer to win \u2014 and he did|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/10/16/the-masked-singer-skeleton-paul-shaffer-interview/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327184247/https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/18/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady/|archive-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sherri Shepherd]], the Penguin in the second season, said she only encountered other masked participants while they were sitting together backstage waiting to find out who was to be eliminated and could only communicate with them by waving her covered hand.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cohn|first=Paulette|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Sherri Shepherd\u2014the Penguin\u2014on Competing Because It Gave Her a \"Tingle in My Tummy\"|url=https://parade.com/951751/paulettecohn/the-masked-singers-sherri-shepherd-the-penguin-on-competing-because-it-gave-her-a-tingle-in-my-tummy/|website=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|date=November 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216150917/https://parade.com/951751/paulettecohn/the-masked-singers-sherri-shepherd-the-penguin-on-competing-because-it-gave-her-a-tingle-in-my-tummy/|archive-date=December 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Cho, Brady, Shepherd, and all other celebrities are trained to use different body language and mannerisms than their own while performing<ref name=\"VAR Dec 11\"/> and are not allowed to talk to anyone except those who wear a special \"stealth cloth\" on the back of their clothing.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> The production crew is discouraged from using their phones for any reason during filming<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> and the audience is prohibited from bringing their phones on set.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\n===Costumes===\n[[File:Marina Toybina.png|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=refer to caption|The costumes for the series are designed by Marina Toybina.]]\nPlestis described the series' costumes as \"extremely critical\" to the show, adding \"so much money\" is invested in them.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Villareal|first=Yvonne|title=''The Masked Singer'' costume designer takes us inside TV's most colorful closet|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233157/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  They are designed by [[Emmy Award]]-winner Marina Toybina who, using a variety of inspirations, develops almost all of the concepts herself. She begins by sketching each costume idea with a pencil and then gives the drawings to one of her friends who creates a digital version. After the costume concepts are shared with the show's producers who decide which designs will be featured during a season, they present each participant with several to choose from. Alternatively, a celebrity may request Toybina design their own costume idea.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/><ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/> She then buys all of the necessary fabrics herself and collaborates with a team of twenty to thirty people to custom-make them.<ref name=\"DH Costume\">{{cite web|last=Grobar|first=Matt|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Marina Toybina Crafted 12 Full-Body Art Pieces In Under Two Months|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913182757/https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|archive-date=September 13, 2019|date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nEach costume costs thousands of dollars to make over two months and the masks are designed to prevent echoes.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/><ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> Beginning as a wire mesh, foam is gradually added around the mask to create an easy-to-wear helmet shape for the performer.<ref name=\"TC Mar 1\">{{cite web|last=Spellings|first=Sarah|title=How Heavy Were Those ''The Masked Singer'' Masks, Anyway?|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#The Cut|The Cut]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233201/https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AVC\">{{cite web|title=How ''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s costume designer dreams up the show's insane outfits|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eShX30efZd8|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 29, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Toybina says she purposely uses foam for the costumes instead of wood or metal as their heavy weight would make the costumes difficult to move around in.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As \"the draping and the handwork [is] all done the old school way\", she cites fashion designers such as [[Alexander McQueen]], [[Thierry Mugler]], and [[Hussein Chalayan]] as inspirations<ref name=\"HP Costume\">{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Priscilla|title=The Maniacal Costume Designer Behind ''The Masked Singer'' Speaks|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|url-status=live|website=[[HuffPost]]|publisher=[[Verizon Media]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915172544/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|archive-date=September 15, 2019|date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\">{{cite web|last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|title=Meet the ''Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Behind Those Elaborate Looks|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222072254/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VF Costume\">{{cite magazine|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=January 23, 2019|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Dreamed Up Those Delightfully Delirious Costumes|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|url-status=live|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915040813/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|archive-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> and says the majority of costumes turn out identical to her sketches.<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> \n\nDue to time constraints, a maximum of two fittings are conducted with each celebrity at a \"very, very private hidden-away\" location<ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\"/> (either the costume shop or Toybina's personal studio)<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> in which the costumes are tested with a vocal coach present to be sure the celebrities can sing and hear clearly.<ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Halterman|first=Jim|title=''The Masked Singer'' Season 2 Disguises by the Numbers|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|website=TV Insider|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928183052/https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|archive-date=September 28, 2019|date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VUL Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=McHenry|first=Jackson|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Costume Designer Breaks Down All 16 Egg-cellent New Looks|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221030001/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> For those who wear a mask separate from their costume's body, either a face stocking is worn or paint is used on the bottom half of their face to disguise their skin color.<ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/> During filming, the participants are assisted by the production crew who helps them take their costumes on and off.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]], the Butterfly in the second season, said this process was short for her (taking only about ten minutes) because the costume she wore was made of only three components.<ref name=\"E! Dec 12\">{{cite web|last=Seemayer|first=Zach|title=Michelle Williams Dishes on Getting Electrocuted on ''The Masked Singer'' Set (Exclusive)|url=https://www.etonline.com/michelle-williams-dishes-on-getting-electrocuted-on-the-masked-singer-set-exclusive-137915|date=December 12, 2019|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408224246/https://www.etonline.com/michelle-williams-dishes-on-getting-electrocuted-on-the-masked-singer-set-exclusive-137915|archive-date=April 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Ibarra, the costumes make it difficult for the contestants to get on and off the stage and their vision is limited when performing on it.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> [[Tommy Chong]], the Pineapple in the first season, said he \"had to be led everywhere\" because of his difficulty seeing.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> As there are no backups, each is sanitized and repaired if needed between episodes.<ref name=\"HP Costume\"/><ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\"/>\n\nFor their work on the first season's finale, Toybina and costume supervisor Grainne O'Sullivan received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming|Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming]].<ref name=\"Emmy 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|title=Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming Nominees/Winners 2019|website=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205042123/https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|archive-date=December 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After the second season concluded, Toybina won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] in the Excellence in Variety, Reality-Competition, Live Television category in recognition of her work on the final episode.<ref name=\"CAG 2020\">{{cite web|title=22nd Costume Designers Guild Awards Winners & Nominees|url=https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|website=[[Costume Designers Guild]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302071147/https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After being worn during a season, the costumes are placed in storage and occasionally taken out for display.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> In the summer of 2019, some of the costumes from the first season were featured in an exhibit, \"Fashion and Fantasy: The Art of ''The Masked Singer''\", at the Los Angeles [[Paley Center for Media]], accompanied by video and Toybina's original sketches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fashion and Fantasy: The Art of ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://www.paleycenter.org/masked-singer-exhibit/|website=[[Paley Center for Media]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421042448/https://www.paleycenter.org/masked-singer-exhibit/|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Selections from the first season were also featured at the annual \"Art of Television Costume Design\" exhibit at the [[Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising Museum]] in Los Angeles from late August to late October 2019,<ref>{{cite web|title=''The Masked Singer'' at the Natural History Museum|url=https://fidm.edu/en/majors/film+and+tv+costume+design/experience/latest+news/The+13th+Art+of+Television+Costume+Design+Exhibition+Opening+at+the+FIDM+Museum+on+August+20%2C+2019|website=[[Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421052307/https://fidm.edu/en/majors/film+and+tv+costume+design/experience/latest+news/The+13th+Art+of+Television+Costume+Design+Exhibition+Opening+at+the+FIDM+Museum+on+August+20%2C+2019|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Slayton|first=Nicholas|title= FIDM Looks at The Clothes That Make The Shows|url=http://www.ladowntownnews.com/arts_and_entertainment/fidm-looks-at-the-clothes-that-make-the-shows/article_d46c2dc2-c924-11e9-b149-37c9dcfc603f.html|website=[[Los Angeles Downtown News]]|date=August 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913201943/http://www.ladowntownnews.com/arts_and_entertainment/fidm-looks-at-the-clothes-that-make-the-shows/article_d46c2dc2-c924-11e9-b149-37c9dcfc603f.html|archive-date=September 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and on February 1, 2020, prior to the premiere of the third season, two of the costumes from the upcoming season were displayed at the [[Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County]] as part of a meet-and-greet promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=''The Masked Singer'' at the Natural History Museum|url=https://nhm.org/calendar/masked-singer-natural-history-museum|website=[[Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421043036/https://nhm.org/calendar/masked-singer-natural-history-museum|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:CBS TelevisionCity02.jpg|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|The series is filmed at [[Television City]] studios in Los Angeles.]]\nThe series is filmed in a 380-seat studio at Television City in Los Angeles, California, on the same [[sound stage]] as ''[[Dancing with the Stars (American TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=The Taco has \"one concern\" for the future of ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://ew.com/tv/the-masked-singer-taco-tom-bergeron-interview/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421011223/https://ew.com/tv/the-masked-singer-taco-tom-bergeron-interview/|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first season was filmed from June 4, 2018, to June 24, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer/tapings/20180601|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421235253/https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer/tapings/20180601|archive-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the second\u2014which introduced an updated set, including a new digital floor<ref name=\"USA Sep 24\"/>\u2014from July 1, 2019, to August 9, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer/tapings/20190701|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421234245/https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer/tapings/20190701|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the third from December 19, 2019, to February 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer/tapings/20191201|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421235741/https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer/tapings/20191201|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><!-- CLICK ON \"FUTURE DATES\" TO LOAD THE SECOND PAGE--> Despite the show having a much shorter filming schedule than most television shows,<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=VanDerWerff|first=Emily Todd|title=''The Masked Singer'' is one of TV's oddest shows. Here's how it was made.|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402114050/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|archive-date=April 2, 2019|date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> filming dates are occasionally moved to accommodate celebrities' other activities.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Choosing to tape the show rather than air it live was a difficult decision, Ibarra said, but one that was necessary because the time commitment would have prevented some celebrities from participating.<ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/> \n\nBefore the performances begin, several vocal coaches and choreographers work with the celebrities for multiple days to determine their strengths and improve their technique.<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\"/><ref name=\"VAR Dec 11\"/> Ibarra said selecting which songs they sing is a collaborative process, with both the performers and producers submitting \"ideas [which] merge as [the songs] go through the [[authorization|clearance]] process.\"<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> [[Ninja (gamer)|Tyler \"Ninja\" Blevins]], the Ice Cream in the second season, stated he \"definitely got to pick the songs\", but the producers wanted them to be [[mainstream]] so that the show's viewers would connect to them.<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\"/> [[Patti LaBelle]], the Flower in the second season, said she was able to select some songs herself but was disappointed in those the producers chose for her, finding it difficult to disguise her natural voice while singing them.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=The Flower says it was blooming impossible to disguise her voice on ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/11/20/the-flower-the-masked-singer-patti-labelle/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126183527/https://ew.com/tv/2019/11/20/the-flower-the-masked-singer-patti-labelle/|archive-date=January 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs filming begins, the studio audience is seated next to the stage and a [[warm-up comedian]] tells jokes to loosen them up. They are then encouraged to scream loudly and chant the names of the costumes enthusiastically while the production crew captures their reactions for later use. Shortly thereafter, the panelists arrive, and the host introduces the first contestant. A clue package plays on the large screen in the studio, and the panelists may choose to write down observations.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> According to Plestis, the contestants have one [[take]] to sing live and their voices remain unedited in [[post-production]].<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/> [[Rob Gronkowski]], the White Tiger in the third season, said this was true; after forgetting part of a song's lyrics during one of his performances, he never received an offer from the show's producers to re-record them afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s White Tiger on not being the only Tiger King on TV right now|url=https://ew.com/tv/the-masked-singer-white-tiger-rob-gronkowski-interview/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416085834/https://ew.com/tv/the-masked-singer-white-tiger-rob-gronkowski-interview/|archive-date=April 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some participants may wear a [[headset (audio)|headset]] inside of their mask to sing instead of a microphone and opt to use one only as a prop while performing on stage.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=''The Masked Singer'' T. Rex has been rude to her friends the last 3 weeks \u2014 but for good reason|url=https://ew.com/tv/the-masked-singer-t-rex-jojo-siwa-interview/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421013634/https://ew.com/tv/the-masked-singer-t-rex-jojo-siwa-interview/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThicke noted that guessing is a challenge for the panelists due to sound issues in the studio often obscuring performers' voices and that it takes multiple performances for them to catch on to who the celebrity might be. Plestis said the panelists' guesses are heavily edited due to their extensiveness and that they are discouraged from researching possible answers to the clues presented to them between the filming of episodes.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"ADW Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Became Broadcast's Biggest Midseason Hit|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513171046/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After all of the performances and guessing concludes, the panelists and audience vote for their favorite performance using electronic keypads. Their votes are then combined using a formula in which the panelists' and audiences' votes are weighted 50 percent each, and the contestant with the fewest formula-adjusted votes is eliminated.<ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/><ref name=\"GD Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Dixon|first=Marcus James|title=How to vote for ''The Masked Singer'': Voting process explained (Sorry, there's no app for that)|url=https://www.goldderby.com/feature/the-masked-singer-how-to-vote-voting-app-1203408226/|website=[[Gold Derby]]|archive-url=http://archive.today/tHocx|archive-date=April 17, 2020|date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Before the participant takes off their mask, the producers film the entire studio audience acting out how they would react to the moment, with only a select twenty \"extremely well-vetted\" people (mostly friends and family of the celebrity) remaining in the audience during the actual reveal.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/> The celebrity is allowed to go backstage to have their hair and makeup fixed before they are unmasked in front of the cameras.<ref name=\"TVL Feb 12\"/><ref name=\"EW Jan 1\">{{cite web|last=Longo|first=Joseph|title=What we saw at a live taping of Fox's The Masked Singer|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/01/what-we-saw-live-taping-masked-singer/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102113745/https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/01/what-we-saw-live-taping-masked-singer/|archive-date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMultiple air-conditioned rooms are located next to the stage which allow contestants to cool down and prevent them from overheating in their costumes. However, mishaps occasionally occur. Toybina said she had to \"reach for the wire and glue\" after the horn of the Unicorn detached during a performance in the first season<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> and while rehearsing in the following season, Williams said she was almost [[electrocution|electrocuted]] after a [[fog machine|smoke machine]] malfunctioned and shocked her, splitting in half the boot she was wearing.<ref name=\"E! Dec 12\"/>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{Main|List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes}}\nThe series is broadcast by Fox in the United States and has been [[simulcast]] by [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] in Canada since the second season. The show is available for streaming in the United States on Fox's website and [[Hulu]], and in Canada on CTV's website.<ref>{{cite press release|title= CTV Unveils 2019/20 Primetime Schedule, Featuring Dynamic Dramas with Big Stars and Big Stories|url=https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607044629/https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|archive-date=June 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://www.hulu.com/series/the-masked-singer-15209f88-6004-4d73-b993-3ff1a244f494|publisher=[[Hulu]]}}</ref> [[Fox Corporation]] distributes the series in the United States and Canada while Propagate Content does so elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title=Fox Partners With Propagate Content to Distribute Unscripted Programming |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017154840/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|archive-date=October 17, 2019|date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Aside from double-length episodes, most run for about 43 minutes and carry a TV-PG or TV-14 [[TV Parental Guidelines|parental rating]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch ''The Masked Singer'': Season 3, Episode 8 \"Old Friends, New Clues: Group C Championships\" Online|url=https://www.fox.com/watch/c2f238d84b5863a804a5455cfc687c05/|website=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Series overview\n| caption     = Series overview\n\n| auxA        = Celebrities\n| infoA       = Winner\n| infoB       = Runner-up\n| infoC       = Third place\n\n| color1      = #375D71\n| link1       = The Masked Singer (American season 1)\n| auxA1       = 12\n| episodes1   = 10\n| start1      = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| end1        = {{End date|2019|2|27}}\n| infoA1      = [[T-Pain]]<br /><small>as \"Monster\"</small>\n| infoB1      = [[Donny Osmond]]<br /><small>as \"Peacock\"</small>\n| infoC1      = [[Gladys Knight]]<br /><small>as \"Bee\"</small>\n\n| color2      = #A8957F\n| link2       = The Masked Singer (American season 2)\n| auxA2       = 16\n| episodes2   = 13\n| start2      = {{Start date|2019|9|25}}\n| end2        = {{End date|2019|12|18}}\n| infoA2      = [[Wayne Brady]]<br /><small>as \"Fox\"</small>\n| infoB2      = [[Chris Daughtry]]<br /><small>as \"Rottweiler\"</small>\n| infoC2      = [[Adrienne Bailon]]<br /><small>as \"Flamingo\"</small>\n\n| color3      = #453842\n| link3       = The Masked Singer (American season 3)\n| auxA3       = 18\n| episodes3   = \n| start3      = {{Start date|2020|2|2}}\n| end3        = {{End date|2020|5|20}}<ref name=\"The Futon Critic\"/>\n| infoA3      = \n| infoB3      = \n| infoC3      = \n}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Viewership and ratings===\n<noinclude>\n{{Television season ratings\n| caption          = Viewership and ratings\n| width            = 100\n\n| link1            = The Masked Singer (American season 1)\n| timeslot1        = Wednesday 9:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| episodes1    